// Section 03 — Speaking
#import "../utils.typ": divider, chevron-break, section-heading, pullquote, callout, section-opener

#section-heading("III", "Speaking")

#section-opener[
There's a thing people do, once they've learned the surface shape of NVC, where they use the form to deliver the same complaints they were already delivering, in a tone that suggests they've done the reading. The complaint is the same; the vocabulary is more careful. The person on the receiving end still feels, somehow, like they're in trouble — just in a more articulate way than before.
]

Speaking with NVC reduces, in its clinical form, to four moves (_OFNR_). People who love acronyms tend to use them as armor, and this one is no exception. The four moves are scaffolding. The scaffolding is supposed to come down once the building stands up.

#callout[
  *OFNR:* _Observation_ — what a camera would have recorded. _Feeling_ — what is in your body, not what they did to you. _Need_ — the universal hunger underneath. _Request_ — concrete enough to say yes or no to. If they can't say no, it was a demand.
]

*Observation.* What actually happened. Not what it means. Not who it makes them.

*Feeling.* What's in your body. Not what they did to you. Not the verdict.

*Need.* The why beneath the feeling. The universal hunger — not the specific thing from this specific person on this specific Tuesday.

*Request.* Concrete enough for a yes or no. If they can't say no, it was a demand the whole time.

#divider

*A short detour into observation.*

Most of what we say to each other is evaluation pretending to be observation. _He never helps_ is an evaluation. _He left the dishes again last night_ is closer to an observation. _She's just like her mother_ is a story. _She raised her voice three times during the conversation about money_ is what happened.

The grammatical fingerprints of evaluation: _never, always, every time, just like, that kind of person, you always make this about, this is so typical of you._ When you hear yourself reach for one of these, the prosecution has already started; there's no observation left in the sentence.

*Feeling and need.*

_Feelings live in the body._ If the sentence has the other person in it, you're not yet at the feeling.

_The need is universal._ Not the version contingent on this specific person doing this specific thing. The need beneath _I want you to text me back faster_ is probably _contact_, _mattering_, or _care_. The particular person is the occasion. The hunger underneath them is older than they are.

#divider

*Request, and the thing recovery folks already know.*

#callout[A request is something the other person can say no to. If no isn't actually available to them, it was a demand the whole time.]

Most people who grew up in households where directly asking for things was dangerous have spent decades issuing demands disguised as requests, or hints disguised as requests, or — most painfully — needs swallowed before they ever reached the level of a request. People-pleasing, codependence, the carefully managed niceness of someone who learned early that wanting things gets you hit, ignored, mocked, or left. _I don't really care, whatever you want_ means something very different when it comes from the partner who has shaped their entire life around accommodating yours.

NVC, read through codependence recovery, is not asking you to become more authentic in some abstract spiritual sense. It is asking the body whose first lesson was _do not want anything out loud_ to want something out loud, in front of someone who could refuse you. That is what the practice costs the people who need it most.

*What it actually looks like, when it goes at all.*

Your friend has been canceling on you for three months. Every time, a good reason. Every time, you say _no worries_ and have mostly convinced yourself it's true. The slight hollow in your chest when she texts to reschedule is data you've been ignoring on purpose.

What you actually feel: dropped. A little invisible. What you actually need: to know you are a real priority, not just an intention.

You've never said this out loud. The version of you who learned early that wanting things has a cost has been editing the ask before it reaches your mouth for years.

Here is the practice, applied: find the thing in the body first. Not the argument. Not the evidence of how many times this has happened. The feeling — something between sad and scared — and the need underneath it, which is mattering, contact, something like _I want to be someone's plan-A at least occasionally._

Then the request. _You always cancel on me_ is a prosecution, not a request. _Are you sure you can make it next time?_ is pre-emptive surrender dressed as a question. A real request is concrete enough that she can genuinely answer it: _Would you be willing to put something in the calendar for next month and actually hold it — not maybe, not let me check, but hold it?_

She can say yes. She can say she genuinely doesn't have the capacity right now. Either answer is something you can actually plan around. Both beat another three months of _it's fine._ _Fine_ keeps you stuck in a room with no exits, politely.

A request doesn't guarantee a yes. That's exactly why it's a request and not a demand. You're handing another person real choice. For people who spent years swallowing their needs, the asking is the bigger risk — bigger than the managed performance of not-wanting it in the first place. It's also the version where anything new can happen.

#divider

NVC trainings frequently become a _new_ arena for the same patterning the practice is supposed to address. The over-empathic listener who never gets a need on the table. The participant who suppresses their own request because they don't want to _create a demand._ The workshop facilitator who confuses self-abandonment with compassion and teaches it to a room full of people who are already losing themselves. NVC can re-install codependence in spiritualized form, with the original cost-of-asking logic now gilded with the moral authority of having attended a seminar. A lot of the time it does.

The mirror version of this trap is worse than the codependent one. Most people don't notice it, because the language sounds correct from the outside.

Someone is being chased around a backyard by another person who is screaming: _Why don't YOU ever even FUCKING try to use NVC? Nothing true is ever said in anger. Why won't you just TRY._

The person being chased stops. And, because they have actually read the booklet, responds: _Okay, I'll try. When you chase me around the yard, yelling and cursing at me to fucking use NVC, I feel a mixture of bewilderment, absurd hilarity, and anger. My only request is that your next actions or words be ones that allow me to go with the joke._

It didn't land. But they laughed inwardly. That felt sane.

_Nothing true is ever said in anger_ — a paraphrase of a common workshop trope, not a sentence Rosenberg wrote — is the old dominator move with new vocabulary. It performs the same structural sleight-of-hand as the is-of-identity: _I am calm, therefore I am right; you are angry, therefore you are wrong_ — but now with the moral authority of a nonviolent communication practice behind it.

Notice what has not actually been established: that the person doing the chasing is calm. They're not calm. They're screaming. They're in pursuit. _Calm_ in this formula is not a description of an emotional state; it's a badge handed to whoever invokes NVC grammar, regardless of what their nervous system is actually doing. You don't have to be regulated to claim the calm position. You only have to be using the right vocabulary while the other person is using the wrong one.

The person demanding NVC compliance while pursuing you is doing something more violent than someone who simply yells. They are enforcing a unilateral disarmament in the same sympathetic activation they are accusing you of. Your anger is rendered illegitimate by the grammar. Their behavior, at any volume, vanishes into the background as the unremarkable default. Tone policing is the name for the move, when it has a name. It doesn't require conscious malice to operate. It works by shifting the entire conversation from _what is being done_ to _how you are reacting to it_. The harm becomes invisible. Your response to the harm is what is now on trial. If you cooperate — soften your tone, reach for the four-step, try to comply — the behavior that prompted the response is retroactively vindicated by your compliance. Your trying is offered as proof that you were the problem.

Both traps end the same place: your interior was the problem, and here is the practice to make you quiet.

What the form does well, when it's used honestly rather than weaponized, is this: when the codependent person tries to assemble the sentence, the structure asks _hang on — do you actually have a request, or are you hoping they'll guess?_ When the controlling person tries to assemble the sentence, it asks _is this a request, or will you punish them when they say no?_ Either question interrupts a particular kind of disappearing — the self-disappearing of the codependent, the consent-disappearing of the controller. Neither is fully escapable from inside the form, not without abandoning the form altogether, which a lot of people do, and which is its own kind of tell.

The form doesn't fix the patterning. The patterning gets fixed by slow uneven work over years, if it gets fixed at all. What the form does is hold up a mirror — your particular survival strategy made visible, sentence by sentence, in the exact way it has been hiding itself inside your particular kind of articulate.

NVC assumes a baseline: both bodies in the room have enough safety in this moment, enough sovereignty in this conversation, enough self remaining to speak from. The qualifier matters — this is not about whether your life is safe in general, or your household is safe overall, only whether right here, right now, your nervous system has any margin left to use the form. Remove that margin and the tool stops applying. The tool didn't fail; the situation changed shape.


What Rosenberg actually wrote is that violence is the tragic expression of an unmet need. The person doing the chasing is unmet somewhere. Also true. The person being chased is also unmet, also scared, also possibly in danger — and their anger isn't a communication failure. It's accurate information about what needs to happen next.

Sometimes that information sounds like: _I am leaving now. This conversation is over._

NVC isn't asking you to stay. _I need to leave this conversation_ is a fully valid request. _I need some space before we talk about this_ is a fully valid request. _I am not willing to be in this relationship on these terms_ is a statement of need as legitimate as any other in the practice.

There's a difference between _NVC doesn't apply here because you're being harmed_ and _NVC applies here, and what it is telling you is to leave._ The second sentence is sometimes the answer. You used the practice, and the practice told you to go.

Once sovereignty is internalized — both kinds, the one that lets you ask cleanly and the one that lets you walk — a quieter grief arrives. You can't guarantee connection. Your stuff sits on your side, theirs sits on theirs. Soft-pedaling needs or swallowing them only increases the distance. Speaking them cleanly sometimes reveals the relationship was never what you imagined. Other people become less threatening; some of them also become sadder, viewed accurately.

#chevron-break

*Lead with what you're hungry for, not what's missing.*

Most of us, when we finally get the feeling and need out, lead with the gap. _I am hurt and I am needing partnership._ True. Useful. There is a related sentence that does different work: _I am hurt — and what I am longing for is more of our days having a sense of partnership in them._

The longing form points at what you'd be moving toward if there were more of it — the direction of the wanting, not just the weight of the lack. The other person gets to feel the shape of what you're actually after, instead of only the absence. Harder to defend against, harder to weaponize, and usually more honest, since most of the time the thing you want isn't the disappearance of the bad version; it's the presence of a better one.

And sometimes, even with the form held lightly and the traps avoided and the language as clean as you can make it, the true thing still doesn't land.

You said the real thing. Found the feeling, named the need, made the request — clearly, cleanly, without a verdict in it. And the other person could not meet you. Wouldn't. Or heard something different entirely and answered that instead. Or went quiet in a way that told you everything.

This is where a lot of people put the practice down. It feels like a betrayal — you did the work, you took the risk, you were honest in a way you'd never quite managed before. And still.

Most introductory material skips the part that comes next: there's grief built into the naming, regardless of whether the other person meets you. You are saying out loud, to yourself first, _this is what I need, and I am not getting it._ Saying it makes the gap real in a way that swallowing it never did. Swallowing kept the door open to a world where maybe you could still get it, if you found the right moment, the right words. Naming closes that door. Sometimes a different one opens. Sometimes it doesn't.

#pullquote[The grief that comes with naming an unmet need is part of what the form is doing.]

The willingness to feel what you actually need — even when the need isn't going to be met, especially then — is most of what the practice is training. The feeling runs its course. The need names itself again later, in a different conversation, with someone who has more capacity.
